The reported problem has been fixed, but I encountered similar problem deeper 
in the stack. The original problem was caused during the build that was 
happening in a separate thread. Trying to open progress monitor dialog by 
passing the workbench shell failed because the display was from a different 
thread.

With that fixed, I now have a problem in loading JavaPlugin that is tripped by 
PDE ensuring that JRE_LIB variable is initialized during startup. Apparently 
JavaPlugin image registry hooks itself to a wrong Display and that causes SWT 
Error to be thrown.

By copy to JDT, the following code in PDE startup fails when PDE is started 
during the build:

IWorkspaceRunnable runnable= new IWorkspaceRunnable() {
      public void run(IProgressMonitor monitor) throws CoreException {
	JavaRuntime.initializeJREVariables(monitor); <-- SWT error in here
      }
};
try {
   getWorkspace().run(runnable, null);
   } catch (CoreException e) {
      log(e);
}

The cause of this error is ImageDescriptorRegistry constructor:

    public ImageDescriptorRegistry() {
	this(SWTUtil.getStandardDisplay());
    }

Looks like the display returned from SWTUtil during the build is wrong.
